{{Apartheid}} The '''Delmas Treason Trial''' (1985&ndash;1988) in [[South Africa]] was the prosecution of 22 anti-[[South Africa under apartheid|apartheid]] activists under security laws, with the intention of suppressing the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]] (UDF).<ref name="NYT">Gerhard, Gail. [https://www.nytimes.com/1990/12/30/books/trial-by-color.html "Trial by Color"], ''New York Times'', New York, 30 December 1990. Retrieved on 3 October 2010.</ref> The defendants included three senior UDF leaders, [[Moses Chikane]], [[Mosiuoa Lekota]] and [[Popo Molefe]], known as the "Big Three".<ref name="sahistory">[http://www.sahistory.org.za/pages/chronology/thisday/1988-12-08.htm "Pretoria Supreme Court sentences 11 "Delmas Treason Trialists""] ''South African History Online'', Pretoria. Retrieved 3 October 2010</ref> Eleven of the accused were found guilty in the same courtroom where [[Nelson Mandela]] was found guilty. Just before the verdict, [[white supremacist]] [[spree killer]] [[Barend Strydom]] started to shoot people in the square outside the court.<ref>[http://www.rosemosswriter.com/books.shouting.html Shouting at the Crocodile, Rose Moss, Beacon Press, 1990]</ref> Their sentences were overturned in 1989 after an appeal to the Supreme Court.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-12-16/news/mn-238_1_south-africa|title=Convictions Overturned for 5 Leading South African Black Activists|last=Kraft|first=Scott|date=16 December 1989|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=14 September 2016|via=}}</ref> The trial was the longest in South African history at the time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/6647432//|title=Activists Convicted of Treason|last=|first=|date=19 November 1988|work=The Salina Journal|access-date=14 September 2016|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>
